00:14:04,243 --> 00:14:06,006
What?
Being photographed.

230
00:14:06,111 --> 00:14:08,204
I just sold two to China.

231
00:14:08,314 --> 00:14:12,080
This is, uh, Bernstein,

232
00:14:12,184 --> 00:14:15,051
and he lived here in Carnegie Hall.

233
00:14:15,154 --> 00:14:17,019
June Carter.

234
00:14:17,122 --> 00:14:18,419
See, this is, uh...

235
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:20,219
You know who she is.

236
00:14:20,326 --> 00:14:21,953
Oh, Tilda Swinton?
Yes!

237
00:14:22,061 --> 00:14:23,358
Tilda Swinton.
Swinton.

238
00:14:23,462 --> 00:14:26,363
Isn't that nice? Mm-hmm.

239
00:14:26,465 --> 00:14:27,830
<i>I was here 60 years.</i>

240
00:14:27,933 --> 00:14:31,334
<i>I'm...
I'm really a, uh, a legend now.</i>

241
00:14:31,437 --> 00:14:32,768
A legend or a fixture?

242
00:14:32,872 --> 00:14:34,840
Well, I'm both,
you know what I mean?

243
00:14:37,209 --> 00:14:38,938
Does Bill live next door?

244
00:14:39,044 --> 00:14:40,978
He's down on the corner.

245
00:14:41,080 --> 00:14:43,605
He's got a tiny little place, yeah.

246
00:14:43,716 --> 00:14:45,183
It's nothing.

247
00:14:45,284 --> 00:14:48,617
By the way,
this is Lesley Vinson,

248
00:14:48,721 --> 00:14:53,249
<i>and Lesley was the art director
of Details Magazine.</i>

249
00:14:53,359 --> 00:14:55,793
<i>The original Details
with Annie Flanders.</i>

250
00:14:55,895 --> 00:14:57,328
We worked well together.

251
00:14:57,429 --> 00:15:01,160
She took me on and didn't mind
how many changes I made...

252
00:15:01,267 --> 00:15:03,394
or how many pictures
I wanted to put in.

253
00:15:03,502 --> 00:15:05,868
The most extraordinary
art director.

254
00:15:05,971 --> 00:15:07,802
Incredible. Um...

255
00:15:07,907 --> 00:15:09,932
The love of Bill's life,
I think.

256
00:15:10,175 --> 00:15:17,581
<i>Details got started
on the ides of March 1982.</i>

257
00:15:17,683 --> 00:15:19,742
The reason I remember that date...

258
00:15:19,852 --> 00:15:23,253
<i>was it was the date that the SoHo
News went out of business.</i>

259
00:15:23,355 --> 00:15:27,416
<i>The vision that I had for Details
was really a continuation...</i>

260
00:15:27,526 --> 00:15:30,757
<i>of what I had been doing
at SoHo News,</i>

261
00:15:30,863 --> 00:15:35,527
<i>discovering people and giving them
their first opportunity to be in print.</i>

262
00:15:35,634 --> 00:15:39,968
<i>The reason Annie founded
the magazine was to give a platform...</i>

263
00:15:40,072 --> 00:15:44,168
<i>to the downtown,
independent, small designers,</i>

264
00:15:44,276 --> 00:15:47,803
<i>who no one else would pay attention
to until they were successful...</i>

265
00:15:47,913 --> 00:15:50,473
<i>and then steal them from Annie.</i>

266
00:15:50,582 --> 00:15:54,040
<i>Oh, Annie was the Earth mother
of downtown.</i>

267
00:15:54,153 --> 00:15:57,987
<i>I don't know if that's
what you called it. Oh, definitely.</i>

268
00:15:58,090 --> 00:16:00,320
Annie would just give Bill like...
Here's a hundred pages,

269
00:16:00,426 --> 00:16:03,657
<i>and Bill flourished with Annie
more than ever anywhere.</i>

270
00:16:03,762 --> 00:16:08,096
<i>It was like she almost gave him his own little
mini magazine just to do it however he wanted.</i>

271
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:10,760
He'd work all day,
and he'd come up at night,

272
00:16:10,869 --> 00:16:13,702
and our sessions usually lasted
till about 4:00 in the morning.

273
00:16:13,806 --> 00:16:16,036
I worked for the Establishment
during the day,

274
00:16:16,141 --> 00:16:21,306
<i>so I was like a bird getting out
of a cage, and I'd go down there.</i>

275
00:16:21,413 --> 00:16:22,971
<i>It was marvelous.</i>

276
00:16:45,537 --> 00:16:48,938
<i>I would come after my job
at the Times,</i>

277
00:16:49,041 --> 00:16:53,137
<i>and we would lay this out,
and then I'd go home about 2:00.</i>

278
00:16:53,245 --> 00:16:55,907
Biked back from SoHo
where we were.

279
00:16:56,015 --> 00:16:59,348
<i>I think one Details
Magazine, it was Fall Special...</i>

280
00:16:59,451 --> 00:17:02,579
<i>125 pages of Bill Cunningham.</i>

281
00:17:02,688 --> 00:17:04,383
A hundred pages?

282
00:17:04,490 --> 00:17:06,617
Ninety-nine.
Ninety-nine pages.

283
00:17:06,725 --> 00:17:08,716
We just...
We never thought of it.

284
00:17:08,827 --> 00:17:12,763
We just went on and did what we wanted
till we had said what we wanted to say.

285
00:17:12,865 --> 00:17:14,992
111 pages.
111 pages.

286
00:17:15,100 --> 00:17:18,763
Here what I did was I blew up
the embroidery of the coat,

287
00:17:18,871 --> 00:17:20,338
and we put it on the pages,

288
00:17:20,439 --> 00:17:22,999
and then put the coat, small,
in the middle of it,

289
00:17:23,108 --> 00:17:24,541
'cause the news was in...

290
00:17:24,643 --> 00:17:27,009
Yeah, the idea was
the big... was this.

291
00:17:27,112 --> 00:17:30,275
'Cause it was like something
out of the Renaissance, you see?

292
00:17:30,382 --> 00:17:33,078
You try to show the reader
what was really new.

293
00:17:33,185 --> 00:17:38,122
Look at this. It's like something
from Paul Poiret, uh, 1910.

294
00:17:38,223 --> 00:17:41,590
Scheherazade,
the Arabian Nights.

295
00:17:41,693 --> 00:17:45,356
Look at the embroidery,
the tassels, the lace.

296
00:17:45,464 --> 00:17:48,228
Now, I mean, can you imagine
the extravagance of these pages?

297
00:17:48,333 --> 00:17:50,130
Annie Flanders never blinked.

298
00:17:50,235 --> 00:17:51,793
You can't say anything, Annie.

299
00:17:51,904 --> 00:17:54,498
I didn't take money,
so I can do what I want.

300
00:17:54,606 --> 00:17:58,770
It's a wonder she didn't say,
"That didn't mean you can bankrupt me."

301
00:17:58,877 --> 00:18:01,437
What I did
from the very first issue...

302
00:18:01,547 --> 00:18:05,074
is I kept a list of how much
Bill would've gotten paid.

303
00:18:05,184 --> 00:18:09,985
Well, the first check I sent him, he came in
the office and ceremoniously ripped it up.

304
00:18:10,089 --> 00:18:12,649
The second check,
he did the same thing.

305
00:18:12,758 --> 00:18:16,717
You see, if you don't take money,
they can't tell you what to do, kid.

306
00:18:16,829 --> 00:18:19,889
That's... That's the key
to the whole thing.

307
00:18:19,998 --> 00:18:21,522
Don't touch money.

308
00:18:21,633 --> 00:18:23,464
It's the worst thing
you can do.

309
00:18:23,569 --> 00:18:25,662
There's a story
about the fact that Bill,

310
00:18:25,771 --> 00:18:28,239
<i>when you sold Details
to Condé Nast,</i>

311
00:18:28,340 --> 00:18:31,832
Bill refused to cash his check.
Yes.

312
00:18:31,944 --> 00:18:35,471
<i>And Si Newhouse was calling you
like every couple of months...</i>

313
00:18:35,581 --> 00:18:37,742
<i>to say,
"Bill, your check is waiting."</i>

314
00:18:37,850 --> 00:18:39,715
Condé Nast bought it?
Yes, yes.

315
00:18:39,818 --> 00:18:41,877
Newhouse bought it
a year ago.

316
00:18:41,987 --> 00:18:44,217
Well, Newhouse is
taking the money.

317
00:18:44,323 --> 00:18:46,348
Yeah, but they don't
own me, you see.

318
00:18:46,458 --> 00:18:48,790
They don't own you.

319
00:18:48,894 --> 00:18:50,862
That's the important thing,
never to be owned.

320
00:18:50,963 --> 00:18:53,693
I know they don't own you.
I know they don't own you.

321
00:18:53,799 --> 00:18:55,198
Money's the cheapest thing.

322
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:57,928
Liberty and freedom
is the most expensive.

323
00:18:59,238 --> 00:19:01,365
No, you know
what I mean, Richard.

324
00:19:01,473 --> 00:19:06,706
So you asked me... about not falling
into the traps of the rich.

325
00:19:08,347 --> 00:19:15,378
I would think it was my first, uh, partner
in my fashion business.

326
00:19:16,555 --> 00:19:18,955
<i>A woman by the name
of Rebekah Harkness,</i>

327
00:19:19,057 --> 00:19:20,888
<i>a very affluent New York family,</i>

328
00:19:20,993 --> 00:19:24,952
<i>and she was looking to invest
in my hat shop and she did.</i>

329
00:19:25,063 --> 00:19:29,500
But then the army came along...
this is 1951...

330
00:19:29,601 --> 00:19:31,091
<i>I was drafted.</i>

331
00:19:31,203 --> 00:19:36,539
<i>Well, they were appalled that I would go,
and their investment would be on hold.</i>

332
00:19:36,642 --> 00:19:37,904
<i>Who knows what would happen?</i>

333
00:19:38,010 --> 00:19:39,375
I was appalled at them.

334
00:19:39,478 --> 00:19:41,639
I thought, "You're drafted.

335
00:19:41,747 --> 00:19:46,548
<i>This is the country where you live,
who you are. You go. "</i>

336
00:19:46,652 --> 00:19:48,813
Well, they couldn't understand that at all.

337
00:19:48,921 --> 00:19:52,220
Course I went in the army.
I wouldn't think otherwise.

338
00:19:52,324 --> 00:19:55,418
They badgered me and they badgered
my family, and finally...

339
00:19:55,527 --> 00:19:58,087
<i>my aunt and uncle,
whom I lived with here in the city,</i>

340
00:19:58,197 --> 00:20:02,190
<i>I think they returned the money
she had invested which... God...</i>

341
00:20:02,301 --> 00:20:04,360
Maybe it was a thousand dollars?

342
00:20:04,469 --> 00:20:06,699
Which was a lot of money then.

343
00:20:06,805 --> 00:20:11,037
To the Harkness family, I don't think
a thousand dollars was a lot of money.

344
00:20:11,143 --> 00:20:13,907
Oh, they tried to have it...
I know what it was...

345
00:20:14,012 --> 00:20:17,140
deducted from my army salary,

346
00:20:17,249 --> 00:20:22,084
which would have taken about ten years,
'cause I don't know what you made...

347
00:20:22,187 --> 00:20:25,645
You got paid maybe $90 a month
or something like that.

348
00:20:25,757 --> 00:20:27,782
Some stupidity.

349
00:20:27,893 --> 00:20:29,656
So my family paid it off,

350
00:20:29,761 --> 00:20:32,730
and then when I got out of the army,
I paid my family back.

351
00:21:08,467 --> 00:21:09,957
Don't take a picture of us.

352
00:21:10,068 --> 00:21:12,229
I'll break that
fucking camera over your head.

353
00:21:19,177 --> 00:21:20,769
Yeah, he wanted...
he wanted me...

354
00:21:20,879 --> 00:21:22,744
to come up
and meet my replacement.

355
00:21:22,848 --> 00:21:24,338
Your replacement.
Your...

356
00:21:24,449 --> 00:21:26,178
Yes, you passed
on the torch to me.

357
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:27,411
You're just a trophy wife.

358
00:21:27,519 --> 00:21:28,952
I was always there
at the beginning.

359
00:21:29,054 --> 00:21:30,954
I've showed her
some of your layouts.

360
00:21:31,056 --> 00:21:33,752
Oh, you teaching, uh...
Uh, I don't teach.

361
00:21:33,859 --> 00:21:36,123
Muffin or is she teaching you?
She's teaching me.

362
00:21:36,228 --> 00:21:38,788
Now, see, you made those
too big, those flowers.

363
00:21:38,897 --> 00:21:41,127
What flowers?
See, that's... that's too big.

364
00:21:41,233 --> 00:21:42,700
Where's the love today, Bill?

365
00:21:42,801 --> 00:21:45,269
Love? Just get the page done.
Show 'em where the love is, Bill.

366
00:21:45,370 --> 00:21:47,702
Show 'em where the love is, right?
Just get the page done.

367
00:21:47,806 --> 00:21:50,297
Winchester.
Winchester.

368
00:21:50,409 --> 00:21:53,469
And he means the gun
off the back shelf of the pickup truck.

369
00:21:53,578 --> 00:21:55,876
John, let me see this one here.

370
00:21:55,981 --> 00:21:59,849
Put your favorite up here.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

371
00:21:59,951 --> 00:22:01,919
You see, it's a little
short coat in here.

372
00:22:02,020 --> 00:22:03,112
Don't encourage him.

373
00:22:03,221 --> 00:22:05,121
The good thing is he can't
hear me talking about him.

374
00:22:05,223 --> 00:22:06,884
Maybe 190.
I don't know what it was.

375
00:22:06,992 --> 00:22:09,620
Then all of a sudden,
when I don't think he can hear me,

376
00:22:09,728 --> 00:22:11,286
he hears me perfectly well.
What?

377
00:22:11,396 --> 00:22:13,591
Bill's fingerprints are all over
everything he does,

378
00:22:13,699 --> 00:22:18,466
'cause he's never ever, ever sold out
one inch of anything.

379
00:22:18,570 --> 00:22:21,164
When the hat business
was sort of sloughing off,

380
00:22:21,273 --> 00:22:23,867
<i>he was working
for Women's Wear Daily as a...</i>

381
00:22:23,975 --> 00:22:25,806
Writing a millinery column.

382
00:22:25,911 --> 00:22:29,813
<i>Part of his falling out with
Women's Wear Daily...</i>

383
00:22:29,915 --> 00:22:31,473
hadn't to do
with anything really big.

384
00:22:31,583 --> 00:22:33,744
It had to do with this
ethical issue for him,

385
00:22:33,852 --> 00:22:38,915
which was that many of his photographs
were being used for an "In and Out" list,

386
00:22:39,024 --> 00:22:44,052
and his feeling is that
it's all equally in.

387
00:22:44,162 --> 00:22:45,993
That's the reason he's documenting it.

388
00:22:46,098 --> 00:22:48,259
He's incredibly kind.

389
00:22:48,367 --> 00:22:52,326
I don't think we've ever seen
a cruel picture done by Bill,

390
00:22:52,437 --> 00:22:58,342
and certainly he's had an opportunity
to really have done it.

391
00:22:58,443 --> 00:23:00,673
He's chosen never to do it.

392
00:23:00,779 --> 00:23:02,542
<i>He was still working
at Women's Wear,</i>

393
00:23:02,647 --> 00:23:06,083
<i>and he did a piece
on women on the street...</i>

394
00:23:06,184 --> 00:23:09,278
<i>in the same clothes
as the models on the runway.</i>

395
00:23:09,388 --> 00:23:13,324
<i>It was about how incredible women
had their own style...</i>

396
00:23:13,425 --> 00:23:15,916
<i>and what they could do
with the clothes, side by side...</i>

397
00:23:16,027 --> 00:23:18,188
<i>with what the designers did
on the runway,</i>

398
00:23:18,296 --> 00:23:22,960
and they changed his copy
to make fun of the women.

399
00:23:23,068 --> 00:23:28,005
This idea of a valuation of one person
over another, or one image over another,

400
00:23:28,106 --> 00:23:30,802
was not something
that he really subscribes to as a person.

401
00:23:30,909 --> 00:23:33,002
He was so beyond upset.

402
00:23:33,111 --> 00:23:37,047
It was so sad and it...

403
00:23:37,149 --> 00:23:38,946
He didn't think he'd ever get over it,

404
00:23:39,050 --> 00:23:41,883
because he was
so embarrassed and upset...

